[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:03.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Jason Brennan, the US

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:05.000
[Amit Varma]: philosopher about the ethics of

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:07.000
[Amit Varma]: resisting state injustice.

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, one of the examples that

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:11.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of struck me from among

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:13.000
[Amit Varma]: the many interesting thought experiments you pose in your book,

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:15.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll just read it out for the listeners.

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Quote, Walker is precedent. He initiates

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:19.000
[Amit Varma]: what is clearly an unjust war,

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:21.000
[Amit Varma]: though many people unreasonably believe it

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:23.000
[Amit Varma]: to be just. Under his command, the

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:25.000
[Amit Varma]: government kills tens of thousands of innocent

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:27.000
[Amit Varma]: civilians and soldiers in foreign

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.000
[Amit Varma]: countries. Thousands of domestic

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:31.000
[Amit Varma]: troops die in vain fighting

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Walker's wars. The war destroys massive

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:35.000
[Amit Varma]: amounts of property and wealth. Tens of

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:37.000
[Amit Varma]: thousands of civilians die from the war's fallout.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Walker now plans to initiate

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:41.000
[Amit Varma]: another unjust war of the same sort

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
[Amit Varma]: in another country. Anne tries

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:45.000
[Amit Varma]: to use peaceful means to stop the war,

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:47.000
[Amit Varma]: but these fail. Anne intervenes.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.000
[Amit Varma]: She kills Walker with a sniper rifle.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:51.000
[Amit Varma]: As a result, this stops the next war

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:53.000
[Amit Varma]: since Walker's successor is less belligerent.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. And, you know,

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:57.000
[Amit Varma]: the point you seem to be making here

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.000
[Amit Varma]: is a fairly straightforward one that

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:01.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, Walker's bad policies

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:03.000
[Amit Varma]: are costing thousands of lives

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:05.000
[Amit Varma]: both of, you know, his own

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:07.000
[Amit Varma]: people and of people in other countries

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:09.000
[Amit Varma]: and it is Anne's

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.000
[Amit Varma]: moral duty and if not her duty

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:13.000
[Amit Varma]: she at least has the right to intervene

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:15.000
[Amit Varma]: and stop Walker and do whatever it takes.

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:17.000
[Amit Varma]: So, my question sort of here

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:19.000
[Amit Varma]: is, I mean, this is again

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:21.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, the most common argument

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:23.000
[Amit Varma]: against consequentialism seems to be

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.000
[Amit Varma]: epistemic arguments that

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.000
[Amit Varma]: geopolitics is so deeply complex,

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:29.000
[Amit Varma]: everything has such unintended

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:31.000
[Amit Varma]: consequences. How can

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Anne or even Walker for that matter

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:35.000
[Amit Varma]: possibly fathom how

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.000
[Amit Varma]: all the chips will eventually fall and

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, what will actually

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:41.000
[Amit Varma]: be the consequence of those actions?

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:43.000
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a good question

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:45.000
[Guest]: and there are some worries about this.

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:47.000
[Guest]: So, let's break it down to a few

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:49.000
[Guest]: different things. So, one is

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:51.000
[Guest]: there might be reasons to defer to police

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:53.000
[Guest]: officers or to government

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:55.000
[Guest]: agents that are epistemic, not

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:57.000
[Guest]: because they have moral authority, but they

00:43:57.000 --> 00:43:59.000
[Guest]: have epistemic authority. So, if I'm

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:01.000
[Guest]: crossing the street and I see two police

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.000
[Guest]: officers beating up somebody

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:05.000
[Guest]: and then I look and down the street

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:07.000
[Guest]: I see two random guys

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:09.000
[Guest]: the same age beating up a third person

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:11.000
[Guest]: I'm more likely to think that the

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.000
[Guest]: police officers are justified than

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:15.000
[Guest]: the random other people. I'm more likely to think that

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:17.000
[Guest]: when it's just civilians beating up another

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:19.000
[Guest]: civilian, it's a mugging. When police

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:21.000
[Guest]: officers doing it, they had some reason.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:23.000
[Guest]: Because, just because of things we know

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.000
[Guest]: about people's behavior,

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:27.000
[Guest]: it's true that sometimes government agents

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:29.000
[Guest]: have more information than we do and in light of that

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:31.000
[Guest]: information, things will be justifiable

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:33.000
[Guest]: but we don't have access to that information.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:35.000
[Guest]: So, we do have to worry about that kind of stuff

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.000
[Guest]: and I have some things to say about that in the book.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:39.000
[Guest]: There's also some worries about

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:41.000
[Guest]: not knowing the consequences of what you

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:43.000
[Guest]: might do, though I think

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:45.000
[Guest]: that that generally helps with self-defense

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.000
[Guest]: rather than not. So,

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:49.000
[Guest]: if you take the

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:51.000
[Guest]: canonical statement of the right of self-defense

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:53.000
[Guest]: or the right to defend others is

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:55.000
[Guest]: a person has the right to

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:57.000
[Guest]: defend himself against an aggressor

00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:59.000
[Guest]: when he reasonably believes

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:01.000
[Guest]: that doing so is necessary to

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:03.000
[Guest]: stop the aggressor from severely

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:05.000
[Guest]: violating his rights or causing severe

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:07.000
[Guest]: harm. That's sort of the canonical

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:09.000
[Guest]: statement. The right to defend others is

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:11.000
[Guest]: the same thing. You just change it from self-defense

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:13.000
[Guest]: to defending others and there's questions

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.000
[Guest]: about exactly what the line is about

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:17.000
[Guest]: reasonable, but what's interesting about

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:19.000
[Guest]: case law and I think most people's

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:21.000
[Guest]: intuitions is that

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:23.000
[Guest]: uncertainty is supposed to fall upon

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:25.000
[Guest]: the aggressor, not upon the person who's

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:27.000
[Guest]: defending themselves. So, there's a nice case

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:29.000
[Guest]: like this in the U.S.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:31.000
[Guest]: There's one person, the aggressor

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:33.000
[Guest]: is mugging a second person.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:35.000
[Guest]: The aggressor is beating him up and the second

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:37.000
[Guest]: person is reasonably in fear of his life.

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:39.000
[Guest]: The aggressor reaches into his pocket

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:41.000
[Guest]: and it looks like he's reaching for

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:43.000
[Guest]: a gun. It turns out that the person

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.000
[Guest]: who's being picked on also has a weapon.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:47.000
[Guest]: He takes out his weapon and he kills the first

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:49.000
[Guest]: person, the aggressor.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:51.000
[Guest]: But it turns out he's wrong. In fact, he's

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:53.000
[Guest]: actually reaching for cigarettes.

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:55.000
[Guest]: I think this guy's going to shoot me. He's actually

00:45:55.000 --> 00:45:57.000
[Guest]: just reaching for cigarettes. I pull out my gun and I shoot

00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:59.000
[Guest]: him. It goes to court and they decide

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:01.000
[Guest]: it's justifiable homicide. They said,

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:03.000
[Guest]: in light of the violence being enacted against you,

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:05.000
[Guest]: it was reasonable for you to think he was

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:07.000
[Guest]: going to get a weapon against you and

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:09.000
[Guest]: the harm should fall upon him,

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:11.000
[Guest]: not on you. You're the one that's the victim.

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:13.000
[Guest]: As the victim, you benefit

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:15.000
[Guest]: from uncertainty. It should not be that the aggressor

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:17.000
[Guest]: benefits from uncertainty.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:19.000
[Guest]: If you believe in moral parity, then

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:21.000
[Guest]: I think the same thing applies to government.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:23.000
[Guest]: It certainly could be the case

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:25.000
[Guest]: that the next time we have something like the Iraq

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:27.000
[Guest]: invasion, when the government says,

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:29.000
[Guest]: they really do have weapons of mass

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:31.000
[Guest]: destruction and if we don't invade them, it's going

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:33.000
[Guest]: to be dangerous for everybody. It's possible

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:35.000
[Guest]: that that's true, but I think

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:37.000
[Guest]: the dangers of the uncertainty have

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:39.000
[Guest]: to fall upon them, not upon us,

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:41.000
[Guest]: not upon civilians.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:43.000
[Guest]: When you think about the

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:45.000
[Guest]: problem of uncertainty, this is one of the reasons

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:47.000
[Guest]: why I would be, practically speaking,

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:49.000
[Guest]: a pacifist. My friend Brian Kaplan,

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:51.000
[Guest]: he's an economist down the street from me,

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:53.000
[Guest]: he's not a pacifist in the sense of

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:55.000
[Guest]: believing violence is never justified.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:57.000
[Guest]: He says, as a matter of government policy,

00:46:57.000 --> 00:46:59.000
[Guest]: it's a good default position

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:01.000
[Guest]: because wars almost never

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:03.000
[Guest]: work out the way they're intended to.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:05.000
[Guest]: It always ends up being more costly

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:07.000
[Guest]: than they expected. They kill lots of civilians

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:09.000
[Guest]: who they weren't supposed to kill.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:11.000
[Guest]: The dangers are much higher.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:13.000
[Guest]: There really are

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:15.000
[Guest]: net benefits to these wars.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:17.000
[Guest]: Even things like, take World War I.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:19.000
[Guest]: The United States intervenes in World War I.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:21.000
[Guest]: Maybe that's part of the reason

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:23.000
[Guest]: why

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:25.000
[Guest]: the Allies beat

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:27.000
[Guest]: the Central Powers.

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:29.000
[Guest]: As a result of that, what happens?

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:31.000
[Guest]: We get Nazi Germany, we get

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:33.000
[Guest]: the Soviet Union, we have another massive

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:35.000
[Guest]: World War. It's not clear that this

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:37.000
[Guest]: intervention was on net positive.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:39.000
[Guest]: It might very well be the case

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:41.000
[Guest]: that had the US just stepped back and done nothing,

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:43.000
[Guest]: the world would have been a much better place

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:45.000
[Guest]: with fewer authoritarian

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:47.000
[Guest]: governments and far fewer people dying.

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:49.000
[Guest]: I think, yes, there's

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:51.000
[Guest]: questions about thinking of that. One other final

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:53.000
[Guest]: bit that I think, because I said this is really multiple

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:55.000
[Guest]: questions stuck together. Sometimes we have

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:57.000
[Guest]: to worry about what you might call the problem of

00:47:57.000 --> 00:47:59.000
[Guest]: fallout. Fannie Kaplan

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.000
[Guest]: tried to assassinate Lenin

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:03.000
[Guest]: back in, I think the year was 1919

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:05.000
[Guest]: or 1921. Anyway,

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:07.000
[Guest]: she tries to assassinate Vladimir Lenin

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:09.000
[Guest]: early on in the Soviet regime.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:11.000
[Guest]: His reaction was to engage in a massive

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.000
[Guest]: terror purge and to murder something like

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:15.000
[Guest]: another million people.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:17.000
[Guest]: One question we have to ask is,

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:19.000
[Guest]: if you know that governments might respond

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.000
[Guest]: badly to your threats, to your

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:23.000
[Guest]: attempts to stop them, does that

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:25.000
[Guest]: provide you with an obligation not to intervene?

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:27.000
[Guest]: I think that's really not special to

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:29.000
[Guest]: government. I think this is another case where it's parallel

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:31.000
[Guest]: to cases with civilians.

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:33.000
[Guest]: If I'm bullying you on

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:35.000
[Guest]: the schoolyard and you fight back

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:37.000
[Guest]: and I credibly say to you,

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:39.000
[Guest]: if you fight back against me, you don't allow me to steal your

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.000
[Guest]: lunch money, well, I'm going to go beat up two other

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:43.000
[Guest]: people and take their lunch money. Do you have

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:45.000
[Guest]: an obligation to let me then beat you up?

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Or are you allowed to defend yourself?

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:49.000
[Amit Varma]: Right, so following on from the thought

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:51.000
[Amit Varma]: of uncertainty, you know, another

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:53.000
[Amit Varma]: question, and I'll come at it from a probabilistic

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:55.000
[Amit Varma]: point of view. Let's say that

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:57.000
[Amit Varma]: Walker is the president, in your hypothetical

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:59.000
[Amit Varma]: example, and he's planning to

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:01.000
[Amit Varma]: go to war. Now, Anne's

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:03.000
[Amit Varma]: certainty of whether this

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:05.000
[Amit Varma]: will be harmful or not can be anywhere between

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:07.000
[Amit Varma]: 0-100%. If it's 0, she

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.000
[Amit Varma]: does nothing, there's no case for her to do anything.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:11.000
[Amit Varma]: If it's 100 and millions of people will die

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.000
[Amit Varma]: if she's 100% sure, then she'll feel

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:15.000
[Amit Varma]: the obligation to stop him. But the truth

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:17.000
[Amit Varma]: is that in the real world, our knowledge is never

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:19.000
[Amit Varma]: 0 or 100. So the question is

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:21.000
[Amit Varma]: A, for Anne to actually

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:23.000
[Amit Varma]: intervene in that situation,

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:25.000
[Amit Varma]: where do you draw the line? How sure

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:27.000
[Amit Varma]: does her knowledge have to be and how do

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:29.000
[Amit Varma]: we account for the human biases

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:31.000
[Amit Varma]: that play into that situation? For example,

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.000
[Amit Varma]: the president could be Republican and

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:35.000
[Amit Varma]: she's from the Green Party, so

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:37.000
[Amit Varma]: those biases also come into it.

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And as a follow-up to that, if you

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:41.000
[Amit Varma]: are thinking of defending

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:43.000
[Amit Varma]: yourself or others against

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:45.000
[Amit Varma]: either a civilian or

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:47.000
[Amit Varma]: an agent of the government, do the

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:49.000
[Amit Varma]: numbers shift? Should you assign

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:51.000
[Amit Varma]: a lower probability of

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:53.000
[Amit Varma]: certainty to the agent

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:55.000
[Amit Varma]: of the state because they could have

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.000
[Guest]: a legitimate reason? Yeah, these are

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.000
[Guest]: all good questions. I'd say the reasonable

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:01.000
[Guest]: person standard for self-defense,

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:03.000
[Guest]: I'd say it's more like a 50%.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:05.000
[Guest]: You think you're about

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:07.000
[Guest]: 50% certain that this is going to

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:09.000
[Guest]: cause some sort of severe rights

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:11.000
[Guest]: violation, then you can intervene.

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:13.000
[Guest]: I think that's around the number. It doesn't have to be close

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:15.000
[Guest]: to 100. In terms of deference,

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:17.000
[Guest]: I think it does make a difference whom you're

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:19.000
[Guest]: dealing with. So I trust

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:21.000
[Guest]: the Swedish government more than I trust the American

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:23.000
[Guest]: government, and I trust the American government

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:25.000
[Guest]: more than I trust the Indian government.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:27.000
[Guest]: So when you told me early on that

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:29.000
[Guest]: there's a very strong culture of deference

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:31.000
[Guest]: to authority and a tendency to put government

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:33.000
[Guest]: up on a pedestal in India, I find that

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:35.000
[Guest]: surprising because when you look at things like

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.000
[Guest]: Transparency International's

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:39.000
[Guest]: measurement of government corruption or

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:41.000
[Guest]: various measures of the degree

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:43.000
[Guest]: of rent-seeking, which is like special interest

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:45.000
[Guest]: lobbying, you tend to find that India has

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:47.000
[Guest]: lots of corruption and lots of special

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:49.000
[Guest]: interest rent-seeking.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.000
[Guest]: So depending on who your government is,

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:53.000
[Guest]: and I'm not saying that to be anti-Indian,

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:55.000
[Guest]: I'm bashing the United States here

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:57.000
[Unknown]: too. I celebrate

00:50:57.000 --> 00:50:59.000
[Guest]: Independence Day. For what it's worth,

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:01.000
[Guest]: I don't wave flags on Independence Day, so I'm

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:03.000
[Guest]: not rah-rah-rah here. But it does

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:05.000
[Guest]: make a difference, the government

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:07.000
[Guest]: in question. So if you're worried

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:09.000
[Guest]: about, say, Russian intervention, it's more reasonably

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.000
[Guest]: worried about Russian intervention than, say, Swedish

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:13.000
[Guest]: intervention, just because of the track record of that

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:15.000
[Guest]: government. But that's true of people too.

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:17.000
[Guest]: If I found out

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:19.000
[Guest]: that my wife was beating somebody up,

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:21.000
[Guest]: I would think that, just given what her behavior

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:23.000
[Guest]: is like and what I know about her,

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:25.000
[Guest]: it's much more likely that she had a

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:27.000
[Guest]: good reason to do that than, say,

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:29.000
[Guest]: some other people I know who I won't mention

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:31.000
[Guest]: who are just not very good people.

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:33.000
[Guest]: Yeah, you're right. The other thing you have to think about is

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:35.000
[Guest]: your own biases.

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:37.000
[Guest]: It's certainly true that when you look in the

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:39.000
[Guest]: U.S., at least, there's a nice book

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:41.000
[Guest]: on this called Party in the Streets by Fabio

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:43.000
[Guest]: Rojas, and I can't remember the name of his

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:45.000
[Guest]: co-author, but they looked at the

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:47.000
[Guest]: anti-war movement during

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:49.000
[Guest]: the Bush era, and they find that

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:51.000
[Guest]: the overall majority of these people who are

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.000
[Guest]: protesting during the Bush era are

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:55.000
[Guest]: not genuinely anti-war. They're just

00:51:55.000 --> 00:51:57.000
[Guest]: anti-Bush. They're Democratic operatives

00:51:57.000 --> 00:51:59.000
[Guest]: or they're part of the Democratic Party, and they

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:01.000
[Guest]: don't like what Bush is doing.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:03.000
[Guest]: Only a very small minority are

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:05.000
[Guest]: sincerely against the Iraq War.

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:07.000
[Guest]: So, if Obama had

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:09.000
[Guest]: done the same thing, they would never have protested,

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:11.000
[Guest]: but the people who are sincerely against it would have.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:13.000
[Guest]: So, when we were making these decisions,

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:15.000
[Guest]: yeah, you have to be aware of your own biases, including

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:17.000
[Guest]: not only your bias to

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:19.000
[Guest]: not give people credit or to be against

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:21.000
[Guest]: them, but also your bias to defer to authority

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:23.000
[Guest]: too, which again, we're all...

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:25.000
[Guest]: If you know about the Milgram experiment, you know that the average

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:27.000
[Guest]: person will execute another person when

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:29.000
[Guest]: they're told to do so.

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.000
[Guest]: These are all the things to take into account.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting when you talk about the

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:35.000
[Amit Varma]: threshold of 50% or the number

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:37.000
[Amit Varma]: could be anything, but I'd contend that

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:39.000
[Amit Varma]: before you act, before you

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:41.000
[Amit Varma]: decide, should I act in self-defense

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:43.000
[Amit Varma]: or the defense of others, and you decide

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:45.000
[Amit Varma]: that, okay, 50% is my threshold,

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:47.000
[Amit Varma]: that 50% is 50% only before

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:49.000
[Amit Varma]: you actually act. After you act, it's

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:51.000
[Amit Varma]: either 100 or 0, because you're going to rationalize

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:53.000
[Amit Varma]: what you did. If you act and you intervene,

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:55.000
[Amit Varma]: say, if Ann kills Walker, she's always

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:57.000
[Amit Varma]: going to say, I was 100% sure. And

00:52:57.000 --> 00:52:59.000
[Amit Varma]: if she doesn't do anything, she'll say, hey,

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:01.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, not sure what can I do.

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:03.000
[Amit Varma]: People don't think in

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:05.000
[Amit Varma]: probabilistic ways and think through

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:07.000
[Amit Varma]: these things. I mean, if you...

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:09.000
[Amit Varma]: And this kind of brings me on to the next question

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:11.000
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, once we

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:13.000
[Amit Varma]: agree that we need a sort

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:15.000
[Amit Varma]: of state, however minimal, but a state

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:17.000
[Amit Varma]: with a monopoly on violence to protect our

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:19.000
[Amit Varma]: rights, doesn't it automatically

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
[Amit Varma]: mean not that they get special immunity,

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:23.000
[Amit Varma]: but that the threshold against

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:25.000
[Amit Varma]: that government is

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:27.000
[Amit Varma]: slightly higher? Because otherwise

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:29.000
[Amit Varma]: if you give, if it is widely

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:31.000
[Amit Varma]: considered morally permissible to resist,

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.000
[Amit Varma]: then anyone with any random conspiracy

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:35.000
[Amit Varma]: theory or any kind of grievance

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:37.000
[Amit Varma]: can rationalize that to do

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:39.000
[Amit Varma]: absolutely anything. So to get

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:41.000
[Amit Varma]: society

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:43.000
[Amit Varma]: running in an orderly way,

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:45.000
[Amit Varma]: isn't it necessary to have a slightly

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:47.000
[Amit Varma]: higher threshold to resist government action

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:49.000
[Guest]: than otherwise? I don't think

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:51.000
[Guest]: so, but for a couple

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.000
[Guest]: of reasons. I think there's, we're conflating

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:55.000
[Guest]: two possible distinctions here, two distinct

00:53:55.000 --> 00:53:57.000
[Guest]: things. One is, what's

00:53:57.000 --> 00:53:59.000
[Guest]: the truth? And the other is, what's useful

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:01.000
[Guest]: for people to believe?

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:03.000
[Guest]: So, suppose

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:05.000
[Guest]: we need a government and it should do certain

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:07.000
[Guest]: things. Like, the cases where

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:09.000
[Guest]: I think violence or other kinds of action would be

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:11.000
[Guest]: justifiable are cases where governments are doing

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:13.000
[Guest]: stuff they shouldn't be doing, like

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:15.000
[Guest]: violating your rights in various ways, hurting people,

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:17.000
[Guest]: shooting people who are pro-

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:19.000
[Guest]: I mean, again, you can go on YouTube and see a bunch

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:21.000
[Guest]: of cases where you can watch an American police

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:23.000
[Guest]: officer put someone on the ground, on

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:25.000
[Guest]: their belly, with their handcuffs tied

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:27.000
[Guest]: behind their back, and then shoot them.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:29.000
[Guest]: And it's like, he's no possible

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:31.000
[Guest]: threat. He's not even a threat to a toddler at this

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:33.000
[Guest]: point. He can't do anything.

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:35.000
[Guest]: These are cases where, like, how could

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:37.000
[Guest]: deference to that possibly be really useful

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:39.000
[Guest]: to get government going? If anything, it's just

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:41.000
[Guest]: permitting government to do too much. It's

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:43.000
[Guest]: dangerous. But that

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:45.000
[Guest]: said, it's true that if you

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:47.000
[Guest]: give people a theory about what they ought

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:49.000
[Guest]: to do, they might misapply it.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:51.000
[Guest]: This is a problem with consequentialist theories in

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:53.000
[Guest]: general. I'm not saying that my theory is consequentialist, but

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:55.000
[Guest]: just to give you an example. So,

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:57.000
[Guest]: consequentialist theories say you should make

00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:59.000
[Guest]: decisions based upon cost-benefit analysis,

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:01.000
[Guest]: do what provides the best outcomes,

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:03.000
[Guest]: and then an objection to that is,

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:05.000
[Guest]: yeah, but people are stupid, and they're not good at

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:07.000
[Guest]: cost-benefit analysis, and many times when people

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:09.000
[Guest]: try to do it, they'll get the wrong answer.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:11.000
[Guest]: The thing that utilitarians will say is,

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:13.000
[Guest]: that's true, and so for many people

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:15.000
[Guest]: it's useful if they simply believe in certain

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:17.000
[Guest]: rules of thumb. So there's a distinction

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:19.000
[Guest]: between what you can call the

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:21.000
[Guest]: criterion of right action, which is the

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:23.000
[Guest]: truth about what makes actions right and wrong,

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:25.000
[Guest]: versus what's a useful decision

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:27.000
[Guest]: procedure for people to use on the ground,

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:29.000
[Guest]: because the best decision

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:31.000
[Guest]: procedure is specific to

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:33.000
[Guest]: you. It's given your psychological

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:35.000
[Guest]: biases, what ways, modes of thinking

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:37.000
[Guest]: make it most likely you'll do the right

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:39.000
[Guest]: thing, as described by the correct theory,

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.000
[Guest]: whatever that is. You find this,

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:43.000
[Guest]: it's not even just a problem in, say, morality, it's a problem

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:45.000
[Guest]: in sports. So,

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:47.000
[Guest]: I don't want to use another American example, but I guess I will,

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:49.000
[Guest]: in baseball, if a person

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:51.000
[Guest]: hits a fly ball into the outfield,

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:53.000
[Guest]: the truth of the matter about where that

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:55.000
[Guest]: fly ball is going to land is given by

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:57.000
[Guest]: a number of equations in physics. You have

00:55:57.000 --> 00:55:59.000
[Guest]: a complicated vector equation that tells you

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:01.000
[Guest]: exactly where the ball is going to land.

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:03.000
[Guest]: As an outfielder, you can't

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:05.000
[Guest]: use these physics equations, because you

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:07.000
[Guest]: don't have access to all the information you need to solve

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:09.000
[Guest]: them, and even if you did, if you knew all the initial

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:11.000
[Guest]: conditions, the angle, the spin of the ball,

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:13.000
[Guest]: the air pressure, etc.,

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:15.000
[Guest]: the angle at which the ball is hit,

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:17.000
[Guest]: with what velocity it was thrown, and so on, even if you

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:19.000
[Guest]: knew all that, you couldn't do the mathematics

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:21.000
[Guest]: in your head fast enough to catch the ball.

00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:23.000
[Guest]: So, what people use on the ground is

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:25.000
[Guest]: something called the gaze heuristic, which is a

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:27.000
[Guest]: on-the-ground heuristic that helps them

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:29.000
[Guest]: catch the ball. It tracks the truth,

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:31.000
[Guest]: even though it's not itself the correct

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:33.000
[Guest]: theory. So, I think that's true

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:35.000
[Guest]: of this theory as well.

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:37.000
[Guest]: It's true that if

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:39.000
[Guest]: conspiracy theorists read this, they're going to

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:41.000
[Guest]: think, ah, I'm justified in doing all

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:43.000
[Guest]: sorts of bad things against government.

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:45.000
[Guest]: That's not what the theory implies. It's

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:47.000
[Guest]: misapplying the theory.

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:49.000
[Guest]: So, it might be that it's useful for people to

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:51.000
[Guest]: have some degree of conformist

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:53.000
[Guest]: behavior, even though

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:55.000
[Guest]: in reality, the conformity isn't

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:57.000
[Amit Varma]: justifiable. You also have a chapter

00:56:57.000 --> 00:56:59.000
[Amit Varma]: on your book on how

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:01.000
[Amit Varma]: it can sometimes be your duty to not follow

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:03.000
[Amit Varma]: unjust orders. And, you

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:05.000
[Amit Varma]: know, some of the examples for this, you

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:07.000
[Amit Varma]: know, will draw us to that intuitively. For

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:09.000
[Amit Varma]: example, you cannot sign a contract with somebody else

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:11.000
[Amit Varma]: to kill a third person because, you know,

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:13.000
[Amit Varma]: you can't infringe on the third person's rights anyway.

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:15.000
[Amit Varma]: So, that kind of contract is

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:17.000
[Amit Varma]: invalid. But how does one act during

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:19.000
[Amit Varma]: war? If your country is attacked,

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:21.000
[Amit Varma]: for example, and there is a war and you

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:23.000
[Amit Varma]: choose to serve, while being choosed to

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:25.000
[Amit Varma]: serve, I would assume that it is

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:27.000
[Amit Varma]: normatively desirable for everyone who is serving

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:29.000
[Amit Varma]: to just follow orders because otherwise

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:31.000
[Amit Varma]: the system breaks down. Everyone can't think

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:33.000
[Amit Varma]: for themselves. So, how do you, and

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:35.000
[Amit Varma]: in the form of war, you can never divine

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:37.000
[Amit Varma]: what actions are just or unjust.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.000
[Amit Varma]: So, how does one deal with that?

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:41.000
[Guest]: Yeah, that's a good question. I mean,

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:43.000
[Guest]: my most basic presumption would be something like

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:45.000
[Guest]: given how war has gone

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:47.000
[Guest]: through history, if you're fighting, you're probably

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:49.000
[Guest]: doing the wrong thing. There have been very

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:51.000
[Guest]: few cases in history where the soldiers

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:53.000
[Guest]: who are fighting should be fighting.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:55.000
[Guest]: So, pretty much,

00:57:55.000 --> 00:57:57.000
[Guest]: in almost any of the European wars that happened,

00:57:57.000 --> 00:57:59.000
[Guest]: they just weren't justifiable

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:01.000
[Guest]: on either side. You're just having land grabs

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:03.000
[Guest]: by various noblemen.

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:05.000
[Guest]: You shouldn't be killing those soldiers and they shouldn't be killing

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:07.000
[Guest]: you. The best argument you can

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:09.000
[Guest]: have is just, well, I've been conscripted and if I

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:11.000
[Guest]: don't fight, they're going to hurt me or hurt my family.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:13.000
[Guest]: If your country has actually been

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:15.000
[Guest]: invaded and they're

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:17.000
[Guest]: attacking, then you

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:19.000
[Guest]: have things like, that's when

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:21.000
[Guest]: just war theory comes in. You can think,

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:23.000
[Guest]: well, we're allowed to use defensive action to repel

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:25.000
[Guest]: them. If I'm attacking

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:27.000
[Guest]: combatants who are clearly in uniform

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.000
[Guest]: and they're clearly the invaders, then that's

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:31.000
[Guest]: fine. The problem, though, is

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:33.000
[Guest]: usually, when people are fighting wars

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:35.000
[Guest]: that are supposedly in self-defense, they're

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:37.000
[Guest]: usually invading another country. Governments

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:39.000
[Guest]: love to take out just

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:41.000
[Guest]: war theory and then say that this

00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:43.000
[Guest]: invasion that we're doing of another country is actually

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:45.000
[Guest]: preemptive, self-defense. They're going to hurt

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:47.000
[Guest]: us. We have to stop them.

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:49.000
[Guest]: So, yeah, I think

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:51.000
[Guest]: it's not really that hard.

00:58:51.000 --> 00:58:53.000
[Guest]: Most of the time, you shouldn't be fighting

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:55.000
[Guest]: and if you're genuinely being invaded, then you

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:57.000
[Guest]: can shoot at the people in the other uniform.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:58:59.000
[Guest]: When they wave the white flag, then you

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:01.000
[Guest]: stop. You don't kill their civilians. You don't

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:03.000
[Guest]: bomb their people. You don't kill their babies.

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:05.000
[Guest]: You don't use chemicals against them.

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:07.000
[Guest]: You don't shoot at people in a village

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:09.000
[Guest]: who are unarmed.

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:11.000
[Guest]: You just shoot combatants on the battlefield

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:13.000
[Guest]: and then when they leave your country, then

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:14.000
[Guest]: you're good. It's over.

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Well, we're almost at the end of our time because

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:18.000
[Amit Varma]: we had one hour and

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:20.000
[Amit Varma]: I'd urge all my listeners to read your book.

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:22.000
[Amit Varma]: There's a lot that we haven't covered. For example,

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:24.000
[Amit Varma]: not just should we follow orders?

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Is it okay to deceive voters?

00:59:26.000 --> 00:59:28.000
[Amit Varma]: The question of does one have a

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:30.000
[Amit Varma]: duty that is an obligation to resist

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:32.000
[Amit Varma]: or does one merely have

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:34.000
[Amit Varma]: the right to resist? I want to end with one

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:36.000
[Amit Varma]: final question, though, which is

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:38.000
[Amit Varma]: and I don't think you addressed it in your book.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:40.000
[Guest]: Should we pay taxes? Yeah,

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:42.000
[Guest]: I guess, you know, at the end of the day, I'm very sympathetic

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:44.000
[Guest]: to anarchism, like genuine, full-blown

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:46.000
[Guest]: anarchism. I think anarchy can work

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:48.000
[Guest]: better than people give it credit for. There's a nice

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:50.000
[Guest]: book on this by Peter Leeson called

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
[Guest]: is it called

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:54.000
[Guest]: Two Cheers for Anarchism? Yeah, Two Cheers

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:56.000
[Guest]: for Anarchism, Why Anarchy Works Better Than You Think.

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:58.000
[Guest]: That said,

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:00.000
[Guest]: you know, I

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:02.000
[Guest]: think there's something to be said for the fair play

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:04.000
[Guest]: kind of argument. Governments are providing certain

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:06.000
[Guest]: kinds of benefits that you are getting

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:08.000
[Guest]: in return and even if it's not consensual,

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:10.000
[Guest]: it's reasonable

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:12.000
[Guest]: to do your part, but

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:14.000
[Guest]: even in light of that, that's only going to justify

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:16.000
[Guest]: some taxes, not usually the amount

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:18.000
[Guest]: of taxes that we're paying. So,

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:20.000
[Guest]: if I'm paying a sugar tariff, there's no reason

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:22.000
[Guest]: for me to pay that. That's just simply unjust.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:24.000
[Guest]: If I'm paying to support

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:26.000
[Guest]: a rent, a government rent, I shouldn't be

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:28.000
[Guest]: paying that. That's unjust. If I'm paying

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:30.000
[Guest]: for special interest things, that's unjust.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:32.000
[Guest]: Most of the military expenditures in the United

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:34.000
[Guest]: States, I think, can't be justified. I shouldn't

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:36.000
[Guest]: have to pay for those. So,

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:38.000
[Guest]: yeah, I actually just

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:40.000
[Guest]: passed in my taxes today, interestingly.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:42.000
[Guest]: So,

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:44.000
[Guest]: I think my tax bill for this year was

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:46.000
[Guest]: $54,000, not including

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:48.000
[Guest]: Medicare and Social Security.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:50.000
[Guest]: So, that $54,000 I paid

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:52.000
[Guest]: to the US government and the other

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:54.000
[Guest]: 15,000 or so that I paid to the state

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:56.000
[Guest]: government, maybe 15

01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:58.000
[Guest]: or 20 of that is justifiable and the rest is

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:00.000
[Amit Varma]: probably not. I think in India, a higher

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:02.000
